facts.text: Appellant is a tenant of the premises in suit owned by the respondent.

anchor.surface_text: The appellant is a tenant of the premises in suit which are owned by the respondent.

facts.text: Premises let out to appellant by respondent under rent-note executed on December 8, 1953.

anchor.surface_text: These premises were let out to the appellant by the respondent under a rent-note executed on December 8, 1953.

facts.text: Appellant permitted to use premises for his Oil Mill.

anchor.surface_text: The appellant was permitted to use the said premises for his Oil Mill.

facts.text: Lease stipulated five years, monthly rent, default for three months allows eviction before expiry and claim remaining rent.

anchor.surface_text: The terms of the lease provided that the appellant was to pay to the respondent the agreed rent every month and in case of default for three months, the respondent was entitled to evict the appellant before the expiry of the stipulated period which was five years, and in that case he was entitled also to claim the rent for the remaining period.

facts.text: On May 2, 1959, respondent sued appellant for ejectment in Court of Munsif, East Jaipur City.

anchor.surface_text: On May 2, 1959, the respondent sued the appellant for ejectment in the Court of Munsif, East Jaipur City.

facts.text: Respondent alleged rent received up to October 31, 1957, thereafter defaults despite demands.

anchor.surface_text: He alleged that he had received the rent from the appellant up to October 31, 1957 and that thereafter the appellant had defaulted in the payment of rent in spite of repeated demands,

facts.text: Appellant's tenancy expired on December 1, 1958 by efflux of time but appellant failed to deliver possession.

anchor.surface_text: His case was that the appellants tenancy had expired on December 1, 1958 by efflux of time, but the appellant nevertheless failed to deliver over possession of the premises to the respondent.

facts.text: Appellant deposited Rs. 1053 to cover rent from November 1, 1957 to November 30, 1958.

anchor.surface_text: He, however, purported to deposit a lump sum of Rs. 1053/- to companyer the period from November 1, 1957 to November 30, 1958 which was due from him.

facts.text: Rent due November 1, 1957 to November 30, 1958 deposited by cheque on December 2, 1958.

anchor.surface_text: It appears that the rent due from the appellant for the period between November 1, 1957 to November 30, 1958, which had fallen in default was deposited by him by cheque on December 2, 1958.

facts.text: Respondent pleaded appellant committed more than three defaults of two months rent each during 18 months.

facts.text: Appellant pleaded respondent waived right by accepting rent.

anchor.surface_text: He also pleaded that by virtue of the fact that the respondent had accepted rent paid by the appellant, he had waived his right to evict him.

facts.text: At first hearing in trial court, appellant deposited Rs. 648 on account of rent due up to that date, accepted by respondent without prejudice.

anchor.surface_text: At the date of the first hearing of the suit in the trial Court, the appellant deposited Rs. 648/- on account of rent due up to the said date and the said payment was accepted by the respondent without prejudice.

facts.text: Trial court found no three defaults of two months in 18 months, dismissed suit.

anchor.surface_text: The finding of the trial Court on the said issue as well as on the other issues framed by it was in favour of the appellant. In the result, the respondents suit was dismissed.

facts.text: First appellate court (Additional Sessions Judge, Jaipur City) held three defaults committed, allowed ejectment.

anchor.surface_text: The appellate Court held that on the facts proved by the respondent, the three defaults had been companymitted by the appellant, and so, he was entitled to a decree for ejectment.

facts.text: Rajasthan High Court dismissed second appeal by single judge, rejected Letters Patent leave.

anchor.surface_text: This appeal was heard by a learned single judge of the said High Court and was dismissed. The appellants request for leave to prefer an appeal under Letters Patent was rejected by the learned Judge.
